From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|weren|lang=enm}}, {{term|werien|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|werian||to clothe, cover over; put on, wear, use; stock (land)|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*wazjaną||to clothe}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*wes-||to dress, put on (clothes)}}. Cognate to {{etyl|sa|-}} {{term|वस्ते|tr=vaste|lang=sa}}, Ancient Greek {{term|ἕννυμι||put on|sc=polytonic|lang=grc}}, Latin {{term|vestis||garment|lang=la}}, Albanian {{term|vesh||dress up, wear|lang=sq}}, Tocharian B {{term|wäs-|lang=txb}}, Old Armenian {{term|զգենում|tr=zgenum|lang=xcl|sc=Armn}}, {{etyl|cy|-}} {{term|gwisgo|lang=cy}}, {{etyl|hit|-}} ''waš-''.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|wears|wearing|wore|worn}}

# To [[carry]] or have [[equipped]] on or about one's body, as an item of [[clothing]], [[equipment]], [[decoration]], etc.
#*{{quote-book|year=1963|author={{w|Margery Allingham}}|title={{w|The China Governess}}
|chapter=5|url=http://openlibrary.org/works/OL2004261W
|passage=‘It's rather like a beautiful Inverness cloak one has inherited. Much too good to hide away, so one '''wears''' it instead of an overcoat and pretends it's an amusing new fashion.’}}
#: {{usex|He's '''wearing''' some nice pants today.|lang=en}}
#: {{usex|She '''wore''' her medals with pride.|lang=en}}
#: {{usex|Please '''wear''' your seatbelt.|lang=en}}
#: {{usex|Can you '''wear''' makeup and sunscreen at the same time?|lang=en}}
#: {{usex|He was '''wearing''' his lunch after tripping and falling into the buffet.|lang=en}}
# To have or carry on one's person [[habitually]], [[consistently]]; or, to maintain in a particular [[fashion]] or [[manner]].
#*{{quote-book|year=1918|author={{w|W. B. Maxwell}}|chapter=10
|title=[http://openlibrary.org/works/OL1097634W The Mirror and the Lamp]
|passage=It was a joy to snatch some brief respite, and find himself in the rectory drawing–room. Listening here was as pleasant as talking; just to watch was pleasant. The young priests who lived here '''wore''' cassocks and birettas; their faces were fine and mild, yet really strong, like the rector's face; and in their intercourse with him and his wife they seemed to be brothers.}}
#: {{usex|He '''wears''' eyeglasses.|lang=en}}
#: {{usex|She '''wears''' her hair in braids.|lang=en}}
# To [[bear]] or [[display]] in one's [[aspect]] or [[appearance]].
#: {{usex|She '''wore''' a smile all day.|lang=en}}
#: {{usex|He walked out of the courtroom '''wearing''' an air of satisfaction.|lang=en}}
# {{context|colloquial|with "it"|lang=en}} To overcome one's reluctance and [[endure]] a (previously specified) situation.
#: {{usex|I know you don't like working with him, but you'll just have to '''wear''' it.|lang=en}}
# To [[eat away]] at, [[erode]], [[diminish]], or [[consume]] [[gradually]]; to cause a gradual [[deterioration]] in; to produce (some change) through [[attrition]], [[exposure]], or constant use.
#: {{usex|You're going to '''wear''' a hole in the bottom of those shoes.|lang=en}}
#: {{usex|The water has slowly '''worn''' a channel into these rocks.|lang=en}}
#: {{usex|Long illness had '''worn''' the bloom from her cheeks.|lang=en}}
#: {{usex|Exile had '''worn''' the man to a shadow.|lang=en}}
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To undergo gradual deterioration; become [[impaired]]; be [[reduced]] or consumed gradually due to any continued [[process]], [[activity]], or [[use]].
#: {{usex|The tiles were '''wearing''' thin due to years of children's feet.|lang=en}}
# To [[exhaust]], [[fatigue]], [[expend]], or [[weary]].
#: {{usex|His neverending criticism has finally '''worn''' my patience.|lang=en}}
#: {{usex|Toil and care soon '''wear''' the spirit.|lang=en}}
#: {{usex|Our physical advantage allowed us to '''wear''' the other team out and win.|lang=en}}
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To [[last]] or remain [[durable]] under hard use or over time; to retain [[usefulness]], [[value]], or desirable qualities under any continued [[strain]] or long period of time; sometimes said of a person, regarding the quality of being easy or difficult to [[tolerate]].
#: {{usex|Don't worry, this fabric will '''wear'''. These pants will last you for years.|lang=en}}
#: {{usex|This color '''wears''' so well, I must have washed this sweater a thousand times.|lang=en}}
#: {{usex|I have to say, our friendship has '''worn''' pretty well.|lang=en}}
#: {{usex|It's hard to get to know him, but he '''wears''' well.|lang=en}}
# {{context|intransitive|colloquial|lang=en}} (in the phrase "''wearing on (someone)''") To cause [[annoyance]], [[irritation]], [[fatigue]], or [[weariness]] near the point of an exhaustion of patience.
#: {{usex|Her high pitched voice is really '''wearing''' on me lately.|lang=en}}
# {{context|intransitive|of time|lang=en}} To pass [[slowly]], [[gradually]] or [[tediously]].
#: {{usex|'''wear''' on'', '''''wear''' away.|lang=en}}
#: {{usex|As the years '''wore''' on, we seemed to have less and less in common.|lang=en}}
# {{context|nautical|lang=en}} To bring (a [[sailing]] [[vessel]]) onto the other [[tack]] by bringing the [[wind]] around the [[stern]] (as opposed to [[tacking]] when the wind is brought around the [[bow]]); to come round on another tack by turning away from the wind. Also written "[[ware]]". Past: [[weared]], or [[wore]]/[[worn]].

